DB["Use of English"][3] = [

  // в”Ђв”Ђ COMPREHENSION PASSAGE 1 в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
  {
    section: "Comprehension",
    passage: `The concept of food security has moved to the centre of policy debates in Nigeria and across sub-Saharan Africa. Food security exists when all people, at all times, have physical and economic access to sufficient, safe, and nutritious food that meets their dietary needs and food preferences for an active and healthy life. Despite being endowed with vast arable land, abundant water bodies, and a largely agrarian population, Nigeria paradoxically imports billions of dollars' worth of food annually.\n\nSeveral structural problems account for this paradox. First, smallholder farmers who produce the majority of Nigeria's food lack access to modern inputs, improved seeds, fertilisers, and irrigation infrastructure. Post-harvest losses, estimated at between thirty and fifty percent of all produce, further diminish what reaches consumers. Second, rural roads are so dilapidated that transporting food from farm to market is prohibitively expensive, causing prices to spike in cities while surpluses rot in rural areas. Third, erratic government policies, including sudden import bans and inconsistent subsidy schemes, have discouraged private investment in agriculture.\n\nThe path forward requires a coherent, long-term agricultural policy insulated from short-term political pressures. Investments in rural infrastructure, storage facilities, and agricultural extension services are imperative. So too is the empowerment of farmer cooperatives, which can negotiate better prices, share equipment, and access credit collectively. Nigeria's food insecurity is not a problem of land or climate, it is fundamentally a problem of governance and investment.`,
    questions: [
      { id:"en3_1", question:"As used in the passage, 'paradoxically' most nearly means", options:{A:"Expectedly and logically",B:"In a way that contradicts reasonable expectation",C:"Dishonestly and deceitfully",D:"With great enthusiasm"}, answer:"B", explanation:"A paradox is an apparently contradictory truth. Nigeria has vast agricultural advantages yet imports huge amounts of food, the opposite of what one would expect. 'Paradoxically' signals an outcome that defies logical expectation." },
      { id:"en3_2", question:"Post-harvest losses in Nigeria are estimated at", options:{A:"Less than ten percent",B:"Between thirty and fifty percent",C:"More than seventy percent",D:"Exactly fifty percent"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Stated directly in paragraph 2: 'Post-harvest losses, estimated at between thirty and fifty percent of all produce.' Direct retrieval question." },
      { id:"en3_3", question:"The writer argues that Nigeria's food insecurity is primarily caused by", options:{A:"Unfavourable climate and poor soils",B:"Overpopulation and land scarcity",C:"Governance failures and inadequate investment",D:"Competition from foreign agricultural companies"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Final sentence: 'Nigeria's food insecurity is not a problem of land or climate, it is fundamentally a problem of governance and investment.' This is the writer's explicit conclusion." },
      { id:"en3_4", question:"'Insulated from short-term political pressures' means the policy should be", options:{A:"Kept secret from the public",B:"Protected from disruption by changing political interests",C:"Enforced by military authority",D:"Funded from foreign sources"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Insulated' means shielded or protected. The writer argues erratic political decisions have already damaged agriculture, so good policy must be protected from those same pressures." },
      { id:"en3_5", question:"Which solution would the writer most likely support?", options:{A:"Permanent bans on all food imports",B:"Immediate privatisation of all farmland",C:"Investment in rural roads, storage, and farmer cooperatives",D:"Relocating farmers to urban centres"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The final paragraph explicitly recommends rural infrastructure, storage, extension services, and farmer cooperatives. The other options are not suggested, Option A contradicts the call for consistent policy." }
    ]
  },

  // в”Ђв”Ђ COMPREHENSION PASSAGE 2 в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
  {
    section: "Comprehension",
    passage: `Artificial intelligence is no longer the exclusive domain of science fiction or elite research laboratories. It has entered everyday life through recommendation algorithms, voice assistants, facial recognition software, and most recently, large language models capable of generating human-like text. Proponents argue that AI offers transformative benefits: accelerating medical diagnosis, personalising education, improving agricultural yields through precision farming, and automating dangerous or repetitive tasks.\n\nYet the widespread deployment of AI raises profound ethical questions. One concern is algorithmic bias, the tendency of AI systems trained on historical data to reproduce and even amplify existing patterns of discrimination. A facial recognition system trained predominantly on lighter-skinned faces, for example, will perform poorly on darker-skinned individuals, with potentially serious consequences in policing or hiring. Another concern is the displacement of workers: as AI systems become capable of performing cognitive tasks once thought to be the exclusive province of humans, entire occupational categories face obsolescence.\n\nPerhaps most troubling is the question of accountability. When an AI system makes a consequential error, a misdiagnosis, a wrongful arrest recommendation, a discriminatory loan decision, it is often difficult to identify who bears legal and moral responsibility. The system's decision may be the product of millions of parameters adjusted through training, rendering the reasoning opaque even to its creators. This 'black box' problem represents a fundamental challenge to the principles of transparency and accountability that democratic societies depend upon.`,
    questions: [
      { id:"en3_6", question:"'Algorithmic bias' as used in the passage refers to", options:{A:"Errors caused by computer hardware failures",B:"AI systems reproducing discrimination from historical training data",C:"Deliberate racist programming by AI developers",D:"The preference of algorithms for mathematics over language"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The passage defines it: 'the tendency of AI systems trained on historical data to reproduce and even amplify existing patterns of discrimination.' Not deliberate (ruling out C), not hardware-related (ruling out A)." },
      { id:"en3_7", question:"The 'black box' metaphor suggests that AI decision-making is", options:{A:"Stored in physically black hardware",B:"Conducted secretly by governments",C:"Opaque and difficult to examine even by AI creators",D:"Encrypted for security purposes"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The passage explains: AI decisions may be 'the product of millions of parameters adjusted through training, rendering the reasoning opaque even to its creators.' The black box metaphor means the internal workings cannot be seen." },
      { id:"en3_8", question:"Which of the following is identified in the passage as a BENEFIT of AI?", options:{A:"Eliminating all human workers",B:"Accelerating medical diagnosis and personalising education",C:"Replacing democratic institutions",D:"Resolving all discrimination"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Paragraph 1 lists: 'accelerating medical diagnosis, personalising education, improving agricultural yields, and automating dangerous tasks.' None of the other options appear as benefits." },
      { id:"en3_9", question:"'Obsolescence' as used in the passage most nearly means", options:{A:"Rapid promotion",B:"Becoming outdated and no longer needed",C:"Violent destruction",D:"Gradual improvement"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Obsolescence means the state of being superseded and no longer useful. Occupational categories face obsolescence as AI replaces human cognitive labour." },
      { id:"en3_10", question:"The writer's overall attitude toward AI is best described as", options:{A:"Unconditionally enthusiastic",B:"Absolutely opposed",C:"Balanced, acknowledging benefits while highlighting serious ethical risks",D:"Completely indifferent"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The writer lists AI's 'transformative benefits' (paragraph 1) but devotes paragraphs 2 and 3 to serious ethical concerns. This balanced, cautionary stance is not blanket enthusiasm, opposition, or indifference." }
    ]
  },

  // в”Ђв”Ђ CLOZE TEST в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
  {
    section: "Cloze Test",
    passage: `The role of women in Nigeria's economic development has been chronically (11)___. Women constitute nearly half the agricultural workforce, yet they own less than ten percent of registered land. Access to credit is similarly (12)___: most formal financial institutions require land as (13)___ for loans, effectively excluding women from the capital needed to expand their enterprises. Cultural (14)___ in some communities further limit women's freedom to enter formal contracts or operate businesses independently. The consequences are not merely (15)___ to individual women, they represent a (16)___ economic loss to the nation as a whole. Research consistently shows that when women have greater control over income, they (17)___ a higher proportion of it in children's health, education, and nutrition than men do. Closing the gender gap in agriculture alone could increase total agricultural output by up to twenty percent. Achieving this requires deliberate policy (18)___: land tenure reforms, targeted credit schemes, and legal provisions that explicitly (19)___ women's rights to property and contract. The (20)___ that a nation can prosper while neglecting half its population is one that history has consistently disproved.`,
    questions: [
      { id:"en3_11", question:"The role of women has been chronically ___", options:{A:"Celebrated",B:"Undervalued",C:"Exaggerated",D:"Misunderstood"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Chronically undervalued', persistently not appreciated at true worth. Chronic means long-lasting or recurring; the passage describes systematic exclusion, making undervalued the right fit." },
      { id:"en3_12", question:"Access to credit is similarly ___", options:{A:"Generous",B:"Restricted",C:"Available",D:"Reformed"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The passage describes barriers (land collateral requirements) excluding women from credit. 'Restricted' matches the parallel structure with the land ownership problem described before it." },
      { id:"en3_13", question:"institutions require land as ___ for loans", options:{A:"Collateral",B:"Payment",C:"Evidence",D:"Reward"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Collateral is an asset pledged as guarantee for a loan, the standard banking term. If the borrower defaults, the lender seizes the collateral. Land as collateral excludes those without land title." },
      { id:"en3_14", question:"Cultural ___ further limit women's freedom", options:{A:"Celebrations",B:"Constraints",C:"Advancements",D:"Innovations"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Cultural constraints (or norms that restrict), the word must convey limitation. The context: freedom to enter contracts and operate businesses is limited by cultural practices." },
      { id:"en3_15", question:"consequences are not merely ___ to individual women", options:{A:"Helpful",B:"Confined",C:"Irrelevant",D:"Obvious"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Not merely confined to individual women' means the consequences extend beyond individuals to the national economy. 'Confined' means limited to a specific group." },
      { id:"en3_16", question:"they represent a ___ economic loss to the nation", options:{A:"Minor",B:"Negligible",C:"Massive",D:"Temporary"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The passage argues strongly for the scale of economic cost, a potential 20% increase in agricultural output is cited. 'Massive' fits; minor and negligible contradict the argument entirely." },
      { id:"en3_17", question:"they ___ a higher proportion of income in children's health", options:{A:"Waste",B:"Invest",C:"Borrow",D:"Conceal"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Invest' income in children's health, the standard finding on women's spending patterns in development economics. Invest here means to channel resources productively." },
      { id:"en3_18", question:"Achieving this requires deliberate policy ___", options:{A:"Confusion",B:"Reversal",C:"Intervention",D:"Celebration"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Policy intervention, deliberate government action to correct a problem. The passage lists specific interventions: land reform, credit schemes, legal protections." },
      { id:"en3_19", question:"legal provisions that explicitly ___ women's rights", options:{A:"Deny",B:"Protect",C:"Limit",D:"Question"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The context calls for provisions that affirm and safeguard women's rights. Protect (or guarantee) fits. Deny and limit are opposites of the intended meaning." },
      { id:"en3_20", question:"The ___ that a nation can prosper while neglecting half its population", options:{A:"Truth",B:"Hope",C:"Notion",D:"Law"}, answer:"C", explanation:"A 'notion' is a belief or idea, often one the writer considers mistaken. 'The notion that...' introduces a false belief the writer is about to disprove. The sentence follows: '...a notion that history has consistently disproved.'" }
    ]
  },

  // в”Ђв”Ђ LEXIS & STRUCTURE в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
  {
    section: "Lexis & Structure",
    questions: [
      { id:"en3_21", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to PERFIDIOUS", options:{A:"Loyal",B:"Treacherous",C:"Courageous",D:"Meticulous"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Perfidious means deceitful and guilty of betrayal. Treacherous shares this meaning precisely. Loyal is its direct antonym." },
      { id:"en3_22", question:"Choose the word OPPOSITE in meaning to MAGNANIMOUS", options:{A:"Generous",B:"Noble",C:"Petty",D:"Gracious"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Magnanimous means generous and forgiving. Its antonym is petty, small-minded and ungenerous. Generous, noble, and gracious are synonyms of magnanimous." },
      { id:"en3_23", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to RECALCITRANT", options:{A:"Obedient",B:"Enthusiastic",C:"Stubbornly defiant",D:"Confused"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Recalcitrant means having an obstinately uncooperative attitude toward authority. Obedient is its antonym." },
      { id:"en3_24", question:"Choose the word OPPOSITE in meaning to SYCOPHANTIC", options:{A:"Flattering",B:"Servile",C:"Independent-minded",D:"Submissive"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Sycophantic means seeking favour through excessive flattery. Its antonym is independent-minded, forming views without seeking approval. Flattering and servile are synonyms." },
      { id:"en3_25", question:"\"Hardly had the governor arrived ___ the crowd erupted.\"", options:{A:"When",B:"Than",C:"That",D:"Before"}, answer:"A", explanation:"'Hardly/Barely/Scarcely + past perfect + WHEN + simple past' is the correct structure. 'No sooner + past perfect + THAN' is the other pattern. NEVER mix them. 'Hardly...than' is a classic JAMB error trap." },
      { id:"en3_26", question:"Identify the figure of speech: \"The wind howled its fury through the night.\"", options:{A:"Simile",B:"Hyperbole",C:"Personification",D:"Oxymoron"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The wind is given a human quality, fury, and the ability to howl it. Giving human characteristics to non-human things is personification." },
      { id:"en3_27", question:"\"The minister threw caution to the winds.\" This means he", options:{A:"Became extremely cautious",B:"Acted recklessly without considering consequences",C:"Resigned from office suddenly",D:"Issued a weather warning"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Throw caution to the winds' means to abandon all careful behaviour and act recklessly. Entirely idiomatic, nothing to do with weather or resignation." },
      { id:"en3_28", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to TRUCULENT", options:{A:"Peaceful",B:"Aggressively defiant",C:"Humble",D:"Intellectually gifted"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Truculent means combatively hostile and eager to argue or fight. Peaceful is its antonym." },
      { id:"en3_29", question:"\"She is taller than ___ of her three sisters.\"", options:{A:"All",B:"Any",C:"Either",D:"Neither"}, answer:"B", explanation:"When comparing one person to MORE than two, use 'any.' 'Either/neither' applies to exactly two. Three sisters = more than two, so 'taller than any of her three sisters' is correct." },
      { id:"en3_30", question:"Choose the word OPPOSITE in meaning to EQUIVOCAL", options:{A:"Ambiguous",B:"Evasive",C:"Unambiguous",D:"Uncertain"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Equivocal means deliberately unclear and open to multiple interpretations. Its antonym is unambiguous, clear and explicit, leaving no room for doubt." },
      { id:"en3_31", question:"Identify the figure of speech: \"Death lays his icy hand on kings.\"", options:{A:"Simile",B:"Alliteration",C:"Personification",D:"Synecdoche"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Death is given a hand and the ability to lay it, human physical attributes. Personification attributes human qualities to non-human abstractions. A simile would use 'like' or 'as.'" },
      { id:"en3_32", question:"\"He bit off more than he could chew.\" This means he", options:{A:"Ate too fast at a banquet",B:"Made a cutting remark to a superior",C:"Took on more than he was capable of handling",D:"Resigned before completing his work"}, answer:"C", explanation:"'Bite off more than one can chew' means to take on a task beyond one's capacity. Entirely idiomatic, nothing to do with food." },
      { id:"en3_33", question:"\"___ he works hard, he will not succeed without discipline.\"", options:{A:"Unless",B:"Even if",C:"Until",D:"Because"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Even if' introduces a concessive conditional, the main clause holds true regardless of the condition. Hard work alone is not sufficient without discipline. 'Unless' means 'if not' and changes the logic entirely." },
      { id:"en3_34", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to LACONIC", options:{A:"Verbose",B:"Using very few words",C:"Poetic and elaborate",D:"Loud and boastful"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Laconic means brief and concise, using very few words. Verbose (excessively wordy) is its antonym. From the Laconians (Spartans) renowned for blunt brevity." },
      { id:"en3_35", question:"\"It was the treasurer who embezzled the funds.\" This is an example of", options:{A:"Passive voice",B:"Indirect speech",C:"Cleft sentence",D:"Conditional clause"}, answer:"C", explanation:"'It was [X] who/that...' is the hallmark cleft sentence, splitting a simple sentence into two clauses to emphasise one element. Here the treasurer is foregrounded as the agent." },
      { id:"en3_36", question:"\"I wish I ___ the examination last year.\"", options:{A:"Pass",B:"Passed",C:"Had passed",D:"Have passed"}, answer:"C", explanation:"'I wish + past perfect' expresses regret about a past event that cannot be changed. 'I wish I had passed' = I did not pass, and I regret it. 'Wish + simple past' is for present unreal situations." },
      { id:"en3_37", question:"Choose the word OPPOSITE in meaning to OBSEQUIOUS", options:{A:"Servile",B:"Fawning",C:"Assertive",D:"Compliant"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Obsequious means excessively fawning and deferential. Its antonym is assertive, self-assured and direct. Servile, fawning, and compliant are synonyms of obsequious." },
      { id:"en3_38", question:"\"Not only did he fail the examination, ___ he lost his scholarship.\"", options:{A:"And also",B:"But also",C:"So also",D:"Yet also"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Not only...but also' is the correct correlative pair. When 'not only' fronts a clause with subject-verb inversion, the second clause must begin 'but also.'" },
      { id:"en3_39", question:"\"Each of the students ___ expected to submit the assignment.\"", options:{A:"Are",B:"Were",C:"Is",D:"Have been"}, answer:"C", explanation:"'Each' is always singular, it refers to one at a time. The plural noun 'students' in the prepositional phrase does not affect agreement. 'Each of the students IS expected...' is correct." },
      { id:"en3_40", question:"Choose the word NEAREST in meaning to INIMICAL", options:{A:"Friendly",B:"Harmful and hostile",C:"Indifferent",D:"Supportive"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Inimical means tending to obstruct or cause harm, hostile and unfriendly. 'Inimical to progress' = actively working against it. Friendly is its direct antonym." }
    ]
  },

  // в”Ђв”Ђ ORAL ENGLISH в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
  {
    section: "Oral English",
    questions: [
      { id:"en3_41", question:"In which word is the letter 'c' pronounced /s/?", options:{A:"Cane",B:"Cot",C:"Acid",D:"Claw"}, answer:"C", explanation:"'c' = /s/ before e, i, or y. In 'acid,' the second c precedes i в†’ /s/. In cane, cot, claw, 'c' precedes a, o, l в†’ /k/." },
      { id:"en3_42", question:"Which word contains a SILENT consonant?", options:{A:"Pencil",B:"Knife",C:"Circle",D:"Candle"}, answer:"B", explanation:"In 'knife' /naЙЄf/, the 'k' is silent. Other silent-k words: know, knight, knock, kneel, knot." },
      { id:"en3_43", question:"The word RECORD used as a NOUN is stressed on", options:{A:"The second syllable: re-CORD",B:"Both syllables equally",C:"The first syllable: RE-cord",D:"Neither syllable"}, answer:"C", explanation:"RE-cord (noun). re-CORD (verb). Same pattern: PER-mit/per-MIT, CON-duct/con-DUCT, PRO-test/pro-TEST. Nouns on first syllable; verbs on second." },
      { id:"en3_44", question:"Which word contains the vowel sound /КЊ/ as in 'cup'?", options:{A:"Put",B:"Full",C:"Blood",D:"Foot"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Blood /blКЊd/ contains /КЊ/ despite the 'oo' spelling, a classic spelling-pronunciation trap. Put, full, foot all contain /КЉ/." },
      { id:"en3_45", question:"Which of the following is a MINIMAL PAIR?", options:{A:"Ship / chip",B:"Think / thing",C:"Bed / bad",D:"All of the above"}, answer:"D", explanation:"All three are minimal pairs, each differing by exactly one phoneme: ship/chip (/Кѓ/ vs /tКѓ/); think/thing (/k/ vs /Е‹/); bed/bad (/Й›/ vs /Г¦/)." },
      { id:"en3_46", question:"In which word does '-ough' represent the sound /Й’f/ as in 'off'?", options:{A:"Though",B:"Through",C:"Cough",D:"Dough"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Cough /kЙ’f/. Though = /Г°Й™КЉ/; Through = /ОёruЛђ/; Dough = /dЙ™КЉ/. '-ough' has at least six different pronunciations, a classic JAMB phonetics challenge." },
      { id:"en3_47", question:"The word IMPORT used as a VERB carries stress on", options:{A:"The first syllable: IM-port",B:"Neither syllable",C:"The second syllable: im-PORT",D:"Both syllables"}, answer:"C", explanation:"im-PORT (verb); IM-port (noun). Same pattern as: EX-port/ex-PORT, RE-cord/re-CORD, PER-mit/per-MIT." },
      { id:"en3_48", question:"Which sentence would typically be spoken with RISING intonation?", options:{A:"Go and sit down.",B:"She graduated with first-class honours.",C:"Are you coming to the lecture?",D:"What a beautiful sunset!"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Yes/no questions typically end with rising intonation, the voice goes up as the speaker awaits a yes/no answer. Statements and exclamations typically end with falling intonation." },
      { id:"en3_49", question:"Which set of words all contain the SAME vowel sound?", options:{A:"Meet, meat, mete",B:"Break, steak, streak",C:"Good, food, mood",D:"Come, home, some"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Meet, meat, mete all contain /iЛђ/. Option B: break/steak = /eЙЄ/ but streak = /iЛђ/. Option C: good = /КЉ/, food/mood = /uЛђ/. Option D: come/some = /КЊ/, home = /Й™КЉ/." },
      { id:"en3_50", question:"Which of the following has the stress correctly placed?", options:{A:"pho-TO-gra-phy",B:"ge-OG-ra-phy",C:"bi-OL-o-gy",D:"Both B and C"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Geography: ge-OG-ra-phy вњ“ (2nd syllable). Biology: bi-OL-o-gy вњ“ (2nd syllable). Photography: pho-TOG-ra-phy, option A incorrectly marks the 3rd syllable. All three -phy/-gy words stress the syllable before the suffix." }
    ]
  },

  // в”Ђв”Ђ NOVEL: THE LEKKI HEADMASTER в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
  {
    section: "Novel вЂ“ The Lekki Headmaster",
    questions: [
      { id:"en3_51", question:"Bepo's 24-year tenure at Stardom Schools is primarily presented as", options:{A:"A tale of financial success and upward mobility",B:"A symbol of unwavering commitment to education against systemic decay",C:"Evidence that private school teachers are superior to public ones",D:"A cautionary tale about refusing to emigrate"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Bepo's years are not financially rewarding, they are morally defining. The novel presents his tenure as deliberate commitment to education and to Nigeria, against the tide of those who have left." },
      { id:"en3_52", question:"The 'Japa syndrome' in the novel refers to", options:{A:"A medical condition affecting Nigerian teachers",B:"The mass emigration of educated Nigerians seeking better opportunities abroad",C:"A government policy restricting foreign travel",D:"Bepo's personal fear of leaving his hometown"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Japa' is Nigerian slang for fleeing or leaving. The Japa syndrome is the wave of educated Nigerians emigrating to the UK, Canada, and other countries, the central social context of the novel." },
      { id:"en3_53", question:"Bepo's emotional breakdown at assembly is best described as", options:{A:"A calculated act to gain students' sympathy",B:"The inciting incident, the crisis that sets the novel's central conflict in motion",C:"The climax of the novel",D:"A flashback to childhood trauma"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The breakdown opens the novel in medias res, it is the inciting incident raising the central question: what broke this man, and will he stay or go? The climax is his eventual decision to remain." },
      { id:"en3_54", question:"Seri's prolonged stay in the UK is portrayed as", options:{A:"Purely selfish abandonment of family and duty",B:"A rational but painful personal decision shaped by Nigeria's systemic failures",C:"Proof she never loved Bepo",D:"A violation of Nigerian law"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The novel treats Seri's decision with nuance. She is a nurse who found better conditions abroad. The separation is a tragedy caused by systemic failures, not personal wickedness. The novel respects her choice." },
      { id:"en3_55", question:"The Lekki setting creates irony because", options:{A:"Wealthy Nigerians in Lekki never experience the Japa pull",B:"Even in Nigeria's most aspirational district, an excellent educator cannot be retained",C:"Only Lagos teachers are loyal to Nigeria",D:"Bepo is materially wealthy despite his title"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Lekki's elite setting heightens the irony, Bepo serves in one of Nigeria's most prestigious areas, yet the pull to leave is still overwhelming for those around him. If even Lekki cannot retain its best, the national picture is stark." },
      { id:"en3_56", question:"Beke Egbin's role as guidance counsellor is structurally important because", options:{A:"She eventually replaces Bepo as headmaster",B:"She is the novel's narrator",C:"She provides an external voice helping Bepo articulate his internal conflict",D:"She persuades Bepo to emigrate with Seri"}, answer:"C", explanation:"As counsellor, Beke Egbin creates conditions for Bepo to voice his dilemma. She is the structural confidant, her conversations with Bepo allow the reader access to his inner world through dialogue." },
      { id:"en3_57", question:"The MOST central theme of The Lekki Headmaster is", options:{A:"The romantic relationship between Bepo and Seri",B:"The tension between personal fulfilment and patriotic duty within a failing system",C:"Academic rivalry between Lagos schools",D:"The dangers of social media for Nigerian youth"}, answer:"B", explanation:"The novel's core tension is Bepo's internal conflict: stay (duty, identity, purpose) or leave (family, comfort, personal fulfilment). Everything, Japa syndrome, Seri's absence, the school setting, serves this central theme." },
      { id:"en3_58", question:"The students lifting Bepo at the novel's end primarily symbolises", options:{A:"A Nigerian cultural ritual for retiring headmasters",B:"The physical strength of Lagos students",C:"The community's affirmation that Bepo's commitment has meaning",D:"Bepo's decision to finally leave Nigeria"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The closing image is the novel's emotional resolution, the community, embodied by his students, validates Bepo's sacrifice. It is symbolic recognition: his decision to stay is honoured by those he stayed for." },
      { id:"en3_59", question:"The title 'The Lekki Headmaster' functions primarily as", options:{A:"A geographical identifier with no deeper meaning",B:"A symbol of identity, what Bepo is, has earned, and would surrender by leaving",C:"An ironic comment on Lagos educators' poverty",D:"A reference to a historical figure"}, answer:"B", explanation:"'Lekki' situates Bepo in an aspirational contested space; 'Headmaster' names his role, authority, and vocation. To emigrate would be to cease being the Lekki Headmaster. The title carries the novel's entire thematic weight." },
      { id:"en3_60", question:"Which statement would the author of the novel most likely endorse about its ending?", options:{A:"It is naive, no educated Nigerian should choose to stay",B:"It condemns all Nigerians who emigrate as traitors",C:"Individual acts of commitment can be meaningful even within a broken system",D:"Patriotism always guarantees financial reward"}, answer:"C", explanation:"The novel respects Seri and others who leave, it acknowledges the complexity of their choices. What it affirms through Bepo is that individual commitment matters and can inspire. The ending is quietly hopeful without being propagandistic." }
    ]
  }

]; // end Use of English


// в”Ђв”Ђ BIOLOGY в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
DB["Biology"][3] = [
  { id:"bi3_1", question:"A microscope image of a cell is 45 mm wide at magnification Г—1500. What is the actual width in micrometres (Вµm)?", options:{A:"30 Вµm",B:"3 Вµm",C:"300 Вµm",D:"0.03 Вµm"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Actual size = image size Г· magnification = 45 Г· 1500 = 0.03 mm. Convert: 0.03 mm Г— 1000 = 30 Вµm. Always convert to the appropriate unit, most cells are 10вЂ“100 Вµm." },
  { id:"bi3_2", question:"A carrier woman for haemophilia (X^H X^h) has children with an unaffected man (X^H Y). What is the probability that their SON will have haemophilia?", options:{A:"0%",B:"25%",C:"50%",D:"100%"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Sons receive Y from father and either X^H or X^h from mother, 50% chance of X^h Y (haemophiliac son). Daughters receive X^H from father, none will be affected. Haemophilia is X-linked recessive: sons need only one recessive allele." },
  { id:"bi3_3", question:"In snapdragons, red (RR) Г— white (rr) gives all pink F1 (Rr). Crossing two F1 plants gives which F2 ratio?", options:{A:"All pink",B:"3 red : 1 white",C:"1 red : 2 pink : 1 white",D:"1 red : 1 white"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Rr Г— Rr в†’ RR (1/4 red), Rr (2/4 pink), rr (1/4 white) = 1:2:1. Incomplete dominance: the heterozygote shows an intermediate phenotype. Compare with codominance where both alleles are fully expressed." },
  { id:"bi3_4", question:"In a dihybrid cross AaBb Г— AaBb, what fraction of offspring are homozygous dominant for BOTH traits (AABB)?", options:{A:"9/16",B:"1/4",C:"1/16",D:"3/16"}, answer:"C", explanation:"P(AA) = 1/4 from Aa Г— Aa. P(BB) = 1/4 from Bb Г— Bb. By independent assortment: P(AABB) = 1/4 Г— 1/4 = 1/16. The full dihybrid ratio is 9:3:3:1." },
  { id:"bi3_5", question:"In a mark-recapture study, 60 fish are caught, marked, and released. The next day, 50 are caught and 15 are marked. What is the estimated population?", options:{A:"200",B:"150",C:"450",D:"900"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Lincoln-Petersen: Population = (1st catch Г— 2nd catch) Г· recaptures = (60 Г— 50) Г· 15 = 3000 Г· 15 = 200. Assumptions: closed population, marks retained, marked individuals mix randomly." },
  { id:"bi3_6", question:"Biomass data: Grass = 10,000 kg; Grasshoppers = 1,000 kg; Frogs = 100 kg; Snakes = 10 kg. Energy transfer efficiency from grasshoppers to frogs is", options:{A:"1%",B:"10%",C:"100%",D:"0.1%"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Efficiency = (higher level Г· lower level) Г— 100 = (100 Г· 1000) Г— 100 = 10%. The 10% rule: approximately 90% of energy is lost between trophic levels as heat, waste, and movement." },
  { id:"bi3_7", question:"Cystic fibrosis (autosomal recessive), two carrier parents (Cc Г— Cc). Of their UNAFFECTED children, what fraction are carriers?", options:{A:"1/2",B:"1/3",C:"2/3",D:"1/4"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Cc Г— Cc в†’ CC (1/4), Cc (2/4), cc (1/4). Unaffected = CC + Cc = 3/4. Of these, carriers (Cc) = 2/4. Fraction of unaffected who are carriers = (2/4) Г· (3/4) = 2/3. This conditional probability is regularly tested in JAMB." },
  { id:"bi3_8", question:"A rabbit population of 500 has 80 births, 30 deaths, 10 immigrants, and 15 emigrants in one year. What is the net growth rate?", options:{A:"9%",B:"6%",C:"5%",D:"3%"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Net change = (80в€’30) + (10в€’15) = 50 в€’ 5 = 45. Growth rate = (45 Г· 500) Г— 100 = 9% per year. Always include all four components: birth, death, immigration, emigration." },
  { id:"bi3_9", question:"The Bohr effect describes how", options:{A:"Increased COв‚‚ and decreased pH shift the oxyhaemoglobin curve right, haemoglobin releases Oв‚‚ more readily in active tissues",B:"Increased Oв‚‚ causes haemoglobin to absorb more COв‚‚",C:"Low temperature increases haemoglobin's Oв‚‚ affinity only",D:"Haemoglobin releases Oв‚‚ when pH rises"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Bohr effect: high COв‚‚ and low pH in respiring tissues reduce Hb's Oв‚‚ affinity в†’ curve shifts right в†’ Oв‚‚ unloaded where most needed. In the lungs (low COв‚‚, high pH) Hb loads Oв‚‚ efficiently." },
  { id:"bi3_10", question:"A student measured tidal volume = 500 mL, inspiratory reserve = 2800 mL, expiratory reserve = 1200 mL. What is the vital capacity?", options:{A:"4500 mL",B:"3300 mL",C:"500 mL",D:"2800 mL"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Vital capacity = TV + IRV + ERV = 500 + 2800 + 1200 = 4500 mL. Vital capacity is the maximum volume exhaled after maximum inhalation. Residual volume (~1200 mL) is NOT included." },
  { id:"bi3_11", question:"Two HbA HbS (sickle-cell trait) parents have children. What fraction will have sickle-cell ANAEMIA?", options:{A:"1/4",B:"1/2",C:"3/4",D:"All"}, answer:"A", explanation:"HbA HbS Г— HbA HbS в†’ HbA HbA (1/4), HbA HbS (2/4 trait), HbS HbS (1/4 anaemia). Only the homozygous HbS HbS has full sickle-cell anaemia. Heterozygotes (trait) are largely asymptomatic and have some malaria resistance." },
  { id:"bi3_12", question:"Which correctly describes the sliding filament theory of muscle contraction?", options:{A:"Actin filaments shorten by folding on themselves",B:"Myosin heads form cross-bridges with actin and pull it toward the M-line using ATP",C:"The sarcomere lengthens as calcium ions enter",D:"Troponin pulls Z-lines apart"}, answer:"B", explanation:"CaВІвЃє from SR binds troponin в†’ tropomyosin shifts в†’ myosin-binding sites exposed в†’ myosin heads bind actin в†’ power stroke pulls actin toward M-line в†’ ATP releases cross-bridge в†’ cycle repeats. Filaments slide; neither shortens." },
  { id:"bi3_13", question:"Which nitrogenous base is found in RNA but NOT in DNA?", options:{A:"Adenine",B:"Guanine",C:"Cytosine",D:"Uracil"}, answer:"D", explanation:"RNA uses uracil (U) where DNA uses thymine (T). Both contain adenine, guanine, and cytosine. In RNA, A pairs with U. Uracil lacks the methyl group present on thymine." },
  { id:"bi3_14", question:"The template strand of DNA is read by RNA polymerase in which direction?", options:{A:"5вЂІ в†’ 3вЂІ",B:"3вЂІ в†’ 5вЂІ",C:"Either direction",D:"From the centromere outward"}, answer:"B", explanation:"RNA polymerase reads the template strand 3вЂІв†’5вЂІ and synthesises mRNA 5вЂІв†’3вЂІ. The mRNA sequence matches the sense (coding) strand with U replacing T. Directionality is fundamental to gene expression." },
  { id:"bi3_15", question:"Turner syndrome (45,X) arises from", options:{A:"A point mutation in a single gene",B:"Non-disjunction during meiosis, a gamete lacked a sex chromosome",C:"Multiple X-linked recessive alleles",D:"Trisomy of chromosome 21"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Non-disjunction = failure of chromosomes to separate during meiosis. A gamete with no sex chromosome fertilises a normal one в†’ 45,X. Trisomy 21 = Down syndrome. Point mutations affect single genes, not whole chromosomes." },
  { id:"bi3_16", question:"Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium requires", options:{A:"Active natural selection",B:"Large population, random mating, no mutation/selection/migration/drift",C:"Only one allele in the population",D:"Small isolated population"}, answer:"B", explanation:"H-W conditions: large population, random mating, no mutation, no selection, no migration, no genetic drift. Any departure causes allele frequencies to change, i.e., evolution occurs. Used as a null hypothesis." },
  { id:"bi3_17", question:"In a population: allele A frequency = 0.7, allele a = 0.3. What percentage of individuals are heterozygous (Aa)?", options:{A:"49%",B:"42%",C:"9%",D:"70%"}, answer:"B", explanation:"2pq = 2 Г— 0.7 Г— 0.3 = 0.42 = 42%. AA (pВІ) = 49%; aa (qВІ) = 9%. Total = 49+42+9 = 100% вњ“." },
  { id:"bi3_18", question:"Which statement about enzyme inhibition is CORRECT?", options:{A:"Competitive inhibitors bind the active site and can be outcompeted by increasing substrate",B:"Non-competitive inhibitors bind the active site and cannot be reversed",C:"All inhibitors are irreversible",D:"Competitive inhibitors permanently alter the active site"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Competitive inhibitors resemble the substrate and compete for the active site. Increasing substrate concentration reduces their proportional impact. Non-competitive inhibitors bind an allosteric site, more substrate cannot overcome this." },
  { id:"bi3_19", question:"A patient has glycosuria despite near-normal blood glucose. The most likely explanation is", options:{A:"The kidneys are producing glucose",B:"Kidney tubule damage reduces reabsorption capacity below normal blood glucose levels",C:"ADH overproduction forces glucose into urine",D:"Glomerular filtration rate is too low"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Normally glucose is fully reabsorbed up to the renal threshold (~10 mmol/L). If tubule transport proteins are damaged, reabsorption fails at lower blood glucose concentrations, glucose appears in urine even without hyperglycaemia." },
  { id:"bi3_20", question:"The light-dependent reactions of photosynthesis produce", options:{A:"Glucose and oxygen only",B:"ATP, NADPH, and Oв‚‚ as a by-product of water splitting",C:"COв‚‚ and water",D:"G3P and RuBP only"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Photolysis: 2Hв‚‚O в†’ 4HвЃє + 4eвЃ» + Oв‚‚. Electrons drive the ETC в†’ ATP. NADPвЃє is reduced to NADPH. Oв‚‚ is released as a by-product. Glucose and G3P come from the Calvin cycle (light-independent reactions)." },
  { id:"bi3_21", question:"Which correctly distinguishes arteries from veins?", options:{A:"Arteries carry deoxygenated blood; veins carry oxygenated blood",B:"Arteries carry blood away from the heart at high pressure; veins return blood with valves at low pressure",C:"Arteries have valves; veins do not",D:"Arteries are thinner-walled than veins"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Arteries: away from heart, high pressure, thick elastic walls, no valves. Veins: toward heart, low pressure, thinner walls, have valves (prevent backflow). Exception: pulmonary artery/vein are reversed for oxygenation status." },
  { id:"bi3_22", question:"Penicillin is effective against bacteria but NOT viruses because", options:{A:"Viruses are immune to all chemicals",B:"Penicillin inhibits bacterial cell wall (peptidoglycan) synthesis, viruses have no cell wall",C:"Bacteria and viruses use different genetic codes",D:"Penicillin kills all cells including human cells"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Penicillin blocks peptidoglycan cross-linking in bacterial cell walls. Viruses have no cell wall, only a protein capsid and sometimes a lipid envelope. Viruses hijack host cell machinery, making selective targeting difficult." },
  { id:"bi3_23", question:"In ABO blood typing, a sample agglutinates with anti-A serum but NOT anti-B. The blood group is", options:{A:"Group B",B:"Group AB",C:"Group O",D:"Group A"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Anti-A agglutination = A antigens present. No anti-B reaction = no B antigens. Blood group = A. AB: agglutinates both. B: anti-B only. O: neither." },
  { id:"bi3_24", question:"Kwashiorkor is caused by", options:{A:"Vitamin C deficiency",B:"Severe protein deficiency despite adequate caloric intake",C:"Iodine deficiency",D:"Iron deficiency"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Kwashiorkor: severe protein deficiency, typically in children weaned onto carbohydrate-rich diets. Symptoms: oedema (swollen abdomen), muscle wasting, skin lesions, hair discolouration. Marasmus = total caloric deficiency." },
  { id:"bi3_25", question:"The correct sequence of urine formation in the nephron is", options:{A:"Glomerular filtration в†’ selective reabsorption в†’ secretion в†’ urine",B:"Secretion в†’ filtration в†’ reabsorption в†’ urine",C:"Reabsorption в†’ filtration в†’ secretion в†’ urine",D:"Filtration only, no reabsorption"}, answer:"A", explanation:"(1) Glomerular filtration: pressure forces filtrate into Bowman's capsule. (2) Selective reabsorption: glucose, most water, useful salts reclaimed in PCT and loop of Henle. (3) Secretion: additional wastes added to filtrate. Remainder = urine." },
  { id:"bi3_26", question:"Which hormone increases water reabsorption in the kidney collecting duct?", options:{A:"Insulin",B:"Glucagon",C:"ADH (antidiuretic hormone)",D:"Thyroxine"}, answer:"C", explanation:"ADH, produced by the hypothalamus and released from the posterior pituitary, increases collecting duct permeability to water в†’ more reabsorbed в†’ concentrated urine. Alcohol suppresses ADH в†’ dilute urine в†’ dehydration." },
  { id:"bi3_27", question:"Stomata open when guard cells become turgid because", options:{A:"They use stored starch for energy only",B:"KвЃє ions move in, water follows by osmosis, increasing turgor pressure",C:"Roots send hormonal signals directly",D:"Wind pressure forces them open"}, answer:"B", explanation:"In light: KвЃє pumped into guard cells в†’ water potential falls inside в†’ water enters by osmosis в†’ cells swell в†’ stomata open. ABA triggers KвЃє efflux in drought в†’ cells flaccid в†’ stomata close." },
  { id:"bi3_28", question:"Nitrogen fixation is best described as", options:{A:"Conversion of nitrates to Nв‚‚ by anaerobic bacteria",B:"Conversion of atmospheric Nв‚‚ to NHв‚ѓ by bacteria using the enzyme nitrogenase",C:"Direct absorption of Nв‚‚ gas by plant leaves",D:"Conversion of protein to urea in the liver"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Nitrogen fixation: Nв‚‚ в†’ NHв‚ѓ, catalysed by nitrogenase. Performed by Rhizobium (legume root nodules, mutualistic), Azotobacter (free-living), and Anabaena (cyanobacterium). Nitrogenase is Oв‚‚-sensitive, leghaemoglobin in nodules maintains very low Oв‚‚." },
  { id:"bi3_29", question:"In primary ecological succession, which is the correct sequence?", options:{A:"Climax community в†’ shrubs в†’ grasses в†’ pioneer species",B:"Pioneer species в†’ grasses/mosses в†’ shrubs в†’ climax community",C:"Climax community в†’ pioneer species в†’ grasses в†’ shrubs",D:"Shrubs в†’ pioneer species в†’ climax community в†’ grasses"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Primary succession on bare rock: lichens (pioneers) в†’ mosses в†’ grasses в†’ shrubs в†’ woodland в†’ climax community (e.g. rainforest). Each stage modifies the environment for the next. Climax = final stable stage." },
  { id:"bi3_30", question:"A leaf in darkness for 48 hours is moved to bright light. COв‚‚ around it first rises, then falls below the starting level. This is because", options:{A:"Photosynthesis always produces more COв‚‚ than respiration",B:"In darkness only respiration occurs; in light photosynthesis exceeds respiration once the compensation point is passed",C:"The leaf switches entirely from respiration to photosynthesis in light",D:"COв‚‚ is converted directly to Oв‚‚ in darkness"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Darkness: respiration only в†’ COв‚‚ accumulates. Light: both photosynthesis (absorbs COв‚‚) and respiration (releases COв‚‚) operate. At the compensation point, photosynthesis rate = respiration rate. Above it, net COв‚‚ is absorbed. Respiration NEVER stops." },
  { id:"bi3_31", question:"Tapeworms lack a digestive system and obtain nutrients by", options:{A:"Photosynthesis through the tegument",B:"Absorbing pre-digested nutrients directly through their specialised body wall (tegument)",C:"Engulfing host cells by phagocytosis",D:"Producing enzymes that digest the host's intestinal wall"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Tapeworms live in the host's small intestine, surrounded by already-digested food. They evolved a highly absorptive tegument (body wall) to take up nutrients directly, eliminating any need for their own gut. Classic endoparasite adaptation." },
  { id:"bi3_32", question:"Which statement about meiosis is CORRECT?", options:{A:"Meiosis produces two diploid cells identical to the parent",B:"Crossing over during prophase I creates new allele combinations on chromosomes, increasing genetic diversity",C:"Meiosis only occurs in somatic cells",D:"DNA replication does not occur before meiosis"}, answer:"B", explanation:"During prophase I, homologous chromosomes synapse and exchange segments at chiasmata (crossing over). This shuffles alleles onto new chromosomes, a major source of genetic variation. Meiosis produces four haploid gametes, not diploid cells." },
  { id:"bi3_33", question:"On a hot sunny day, a well-watered plant wilts. The most accurate explanation is", options:{A:"Roots have stopped absorbing water",B:"Transpiration rate exceeds absorption rate, cells lose turgor",C:"Excess light has stopped photosynthesis",D:"Stomata open too wide, blocking water uptake"}, answer:"B", explanation:"On hot, dry, windy days, transpiration rate spikes. If water loss exceeds root absorption, cells lose turgor and the plant wilts. Guard cells also lose turgidity в†’ stomata close, reducing further water loss. Recovery occurs when deficit is corrected." },
  { id:"bi3_34", question:"Mycorrhizal fungi form associations with plant roots that are best described as", options:{A:"Parasitic, they reduce plant mineral uptake",B:"Mutualistic, fungi extend absorptive surface for minerals (especially phosphorus) in exchange for plant carbohydrates",C:"Commensal, the plant benefits; the fungus is unaffected",D:"Pathogenic, they cause root disease"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Mycorrhizae are found on over 80% of land plant species. Fungal hyphae vastly increase mineral and water uptake. The plant provides photosynthate. Both benefit: classic mutualism. Particularly critical for phosphorus uptake in poor soils." },
  { id:"bi3_35", question:"The carrying capacity (K) of an environment is defined as", options:{A:"The maximum rate of population growth",B:"The maximum population size the environment can sustainably support",C:"The minimum viable population size",D:"Total ecosystem biomass"}, answer:"B", explanation:"K is the upper asymptote of the logistic (S-shaped) growth curve. As population approaches K, limiting resources cause birth rate to fall and/or death rate to rise until they balance. Overshoot leads to population crash." },
  { id:"bi3_36", question:"The correct sequence of events at a neuromuscular junction is", options:{A:"Action potential в†’ CaВІвЃє influx в†’ ACh release в†’ receptor binding в†’ muscle depolarisation",B:"ACh release в†’ CaВІвЃє influx в†’ action potential в†’ contraction",C:"Action potential в†’ muscle depolarisation в†’ CaВІвЃє influx в†’ ACh release",D:"Receptor binding в†’ ACh synthesis в†’ CaВІвЃє influx в†’ action potential"}, answer:"A", explanation:"(1) Action potential arrives at axon terminal. (2) Voltage-gated CaВІвЃє channels open. (3) Vesicles fuse в†’ ACh released into cleft. (4) ACh binds nicotinic receptors on muscle в†’ depolarisation в†’ contraction. Acetylcholinesterase then breaks down ACh." },
  { id:"bi3_37", question:"A patient is injected with ready-made antibodies after suspected rabies exposure. This type of immunity is", options:{A:"Active natural",B:"Active artificial",C:"Passive artificial",D:"Passive natural"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Passive = antibodies supplied externally (patient does not make own). Artificial = administered deliberately by humans. Passive immunity is fast but short-lived. Active immunity (vaccine) takes longer but produces memory cells в†’ long-lasting protection." },
  { id:"bi3_38", question:"Which correctly compares the endocrine and nervous systems?", options:{A:"Nervous system uses chemical signals only; endocrine uses electrical",B:"Nervous responses are fast and short-lived; endocrine responses are slower but longer-lasting",C:"Endocrine controls voluntary movement; nervous controls hormone balance",D:"Both operate exclusively through the bloodstream"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Nervous: fast (milliseconds), localised, short-lived (electrical impulse + chemical synapse). Endocrine: slower (seconds to hours), widespread via bloodstream, longer-lasting. These are complementary regulatory systems." },
  { id:"bi3_39", question:"The heart sounds 'lub-dub' are caused by", options:{A:"Lub = semilunar valves closing; Dub = AV valves closing",B:"Lub = AV valves closing at start of ventricular systole; Dub = semilunar valves closing at end of ventricular systole",C:"Lub = atrial systole; Dub = ventricular systole",D:"Both sounds result from blood hitting the ventricular walls"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Lub (S1): AV valves (mitral + tricuspid) close at start of ventricular systole, preventing backflow to atria. Dub (S2): semilunar valves (aortic + pulmonary) close at end of ventricular systole, preventing arterial backflow. Valve defects = murmurs." },
  { id:"bi3_40", question:"After ovulation, the ruptured follicle becomes the corpus luteum, which", options:{A:"Produces FSH to trigger the next cycle",B:"Secretes progesterone and oestrogen to maintain the uterine lining for implantation",C:"Stores eggs for future ovulation",D:"Produces LH to stimulate the ovary"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Corpus luteum secretes progesterone (mainly) and oestrogen, maintaining the thickened endometrium for potential implantation. If fertilisation does not occur, the corpus luteum degenerates в†’ progesterone falls в†’ menstruation begins." }
]; // end Biology


// в”Ђв”Ђ CHEMISTRY в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
DB["Chemistry"][3] = [
  { id:"ch3_1", question:"0.5 mol/dmВі Hв‚‚SOв‚„ is diluted by adding an equal volume of water. What is the new concentration?", options:{A:"1.0 mol/dmВі",B:"0.25 mol/dmВі",C:"0.5 mol/dmВі",D:"0.1 mol/dmВі"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Cв‚ЃVв‚Ѓ = Cв‚‚Vв‚‚. 0.5 Г— V = Cв‚‚ Г— 2V в†’ Cв‚‚ = 0.25 mol/dmВі. Doubling volume halves concentration. Moles of Hв‚‚SOв‚„ are unchanged, only the volume changes." },
  { id:"ch3_2", question:"20 cmВі of 0.15 mol/dmВі Naв‚‚COв‚ѓ is neutralised by 0.25 mol/dmВі HCl. What volume of HCl is needed? (Naв‚‚COв‚ѓ + 2HCl в†’ 2NaCl + Hв‚‚O + COв‚‚)", options:{A:"12 cmВі",B:"24 cmВі",C:"6 cmВі",D:"48 cmВі"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Moles Naв‚‚COв‚ѓ = 0.15 Г— 0.020 = 0.003 mol. Equation ratio 1:2 в†’ moles HCl = 0.006 mol. Volume = 0.006 Г· 0.25 = 0.024 dmВі = 24 cmВі. Always apply the mole ratio from the balanced equation." },
  { id:"ch3_3", question:"What mass of iron is produced from 320 g of Feв‚‚Oв‚ѓ in the blast furnace? (Feв‚‚Oв‚ѓ + 3CO в†’ 2Fe + 3COв‚‚; Fe=56, O=16)", options:{A:"224 g",B:"112 g",C:"56 g",D:"448 g"}, answer:"A", explanation:"M(Feв‚‚Oв‚ѓ) = 160 g/mol. Moles Feв‚‚Oв‚ѓ = 320 Г· 160 = 2 mol. Ratio 1:2 в†’ moles Fe = 4 mol. Mass Fe = 4 Г— 56 = 224 g." },
  { id:"ch3_4", question:"A compound contains 27.3% C and 72.7% O by mass. What is its empirical formula? (C=12, O=16)", options:{A:"COв‚‚",B:"CO",C:"Cв‚‚Oв‚ѓ",D:"Cв‚ѓOв‚‚"}, answer:"A", explanation:"C: 27.3 Г· 12 = 2.275; O: 72.7 Г· 16 = 4.544. Divide by smallest: C = 1; O = 4.544 Г· 2.275 в‰€ 2. Empirical formula = COв‚‚." },
  { id:"ch3_5", question:"A gas occupies 600 cmВі at 300 K and 150 kPa. What volume at 400 K and 200 kPa?", options:{A:"600 cmВі",B:"300 cmВі",C:"800 cmВі",D:"450 cmВі"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Pв‚ЃVв‚Ѓ/Tв‚Ѓ = Pв‚‚Vв‚‚/Tв‚‚. Vв‚‚ = (150 Г— 600 Г— 400) Г· (300 Г— 200) = 36,000,000 Г· 60,000 = 600 cmВі. Temperature increase and pressure increase exactly cancel each other." },
  { id:"ch3_6", question:"In the electrolysis of dilute NaOH solution, what is produced at each electrode?", options:{A:"Na at cathode, Oв‚‚ at anode",B:"Hв‚‚ at cathode, Oв‚‚ at anode",C:"Oв‚‚ at cathode, Hв‚‚ at anode",D:"Hв‚‚ at cathode, Clв‚‚ at anode"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Cathode (reduction): 2HвЃє + 2eвЃ» в†’ Hв‚‚. Anode (oxidation): 4OHвЃ» в†’ 2Hв‚‚O + Oв‚‚ + 4eвЃ». NaвЃє remains in solution, too reactive to deposit from aqueous solution. Volume ratio Hв‚‚:Oв‚‚ = 2:1." },
  { id:"ch3_7", question:"Combustion enthalpy of methane = в€’890 kJ/mol. How much energy is released burning 8 g of methane? (CHв‚„, M = 16)", options:{A:"445 kJ",B:"3560 kJ",C:"890 kJ",D:"222.5 kJ"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Moles CHв‚„ = 8 Г· 16 = 0.5 mol. Energy = 0.5 Г— 890 = 445 kJ. Negative sign indicates exothermic, energy is released to surroundings." },
  { id:"ch3_8", question:"2.4 g of carbon is burned completely in excess Oв‚‚. What volume of COв‚‚ is produced at STP? (C=12, molar volume = 22.4 L/mol)", options:{A:"4.48 L",B:"2.24 L",C:"44.8 L",D:"22.4 L"}, answer:"A", explanation:"C + Oв‚‚ в†’ COв‚‚. Moles C = 2.4 Г· 12 = 0.2 mol. 1:1 ratio в†’ moles COв‚‚ = 0.2 mol. Volume = 0.2 Г— 22.4 = 4.48 L." },
  { id:"ch3_9", question:"For PClв‚…(g) в‡Њ PClв‚ѓ(g) + Clв‚‚(g), what happens when total pressure is increased?", options:{A:"Shifts right, more products",B:"Shifts left, fewer moles of gas on the left",C:"No change, pressure doesn't affect equilibria",D:"Shifts left, right side has more moles of gas; higher pressure favours fewer moles"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Le Chatelier: increased pressure favours fewer moles of gas. Left: 1 mol. Right: 2 mol. Equilibrium shifts LEFT. If equal moles on both sides, pressure has no effect on position." },
  { id:"ch3_10", question:"If 5.6 g of iron is actually produced when the theoretical yield is 8.4 g, what is the percentage yield?", options:{A:"66.7%",B:"33.3%",C:"150%",D:"56%"}, answer:"A", explanation:"% yield = (actual Г· theoretical) Г— 100 = (5.6 Г· 8.4) Г— 100 = 66.7%. Yield is always в‰¤ 100%. Lower yields arise from reversible reactions, side reactions, losses during transfer, or impure reactants." },
  { id:"ch3_11", question:"The concentration of HвЃє ions in a solution is 0.001 mol/dmВі. What is the pH?", options:{A:"pH = 1",B:"pH = 3",C:"pH = 11",D:"pH = 7"}, answer:"B", explanation:"pH = в€’log[HвЃє] = в€’log(10вЃ»Ві) = 3. Acidic solution. Rule: if [HвЃє] = 10вЃ»вЃї mol/dmВі, then pH = n." },
  { id:"ch3_12", question:"Which reagent pair produces a WHITE precipitate in aqueous solution?", options:{A:"NaCl(aq) + KNOв‚ѓ(aq)",B:"BaClв‚‚(aq) + Naв‚‚SOв‚„(aq)",C:"KCl(aq) + NaOH(aq)",D:"MgClв‚‚(aq) + HCl(aq)"}, answer:"B", explanation:"BaClв‚‚ + Naв‚‚SOв‚„ в†’ BaSOв‚„в†“ (white) + 2NaCl. BaSOв‚„ is insoluble, the standard test for sulphate ions: add dilute HCl then BaClв‚‚; white precipitate confirms SOв‚„ВІвЃ»." },
  { id:"ch3_13", question:"NaOH solution is added to FeВІвЃє and FeВівЃє separately. The precipitate colours are", options:{A:"White; green",B:"Green; reddish-brown",C:"Blue; white",D:"Reddish-brown; green"}, answer:"B", explanation:"FeВІвЃє + 2OHвЃ» в†’ Fe(OH)в‚‚ (green precipitate). FeВівЃє + 3OHвЃ» в†’ Fe(OH)в‚ѓ (reddish-brown precipitate). These colour differences are the standard qualitative test for distinguishing FeВІвЃє from FeВівЃє in JAMB chemistry." },
  { id:"ch3_14", question:"An organic compound gives a brick-red precipitate with Fehling's solution AND decolourises bromine water. It most likely contains", options:{A:"An alcohol group only",B:"A carboxylic acid group only",C:"Both an aldehyde group and a C=C double bond",D:"A ketone group only"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Fehling's positive = reducing agent (aldehyde group). Bromine water decolourised = C=C double bond (alkene). A compound that does both contains BOTH functional groups. Ketones do not reduce Fehling's." },
  { id:"ch3_15", question:"What volume of 2 mol/dmВі HCl is needed to dissolve 4.05 g of aluminium? (Al=27; 2Al + 6HCl в†’ 2AlClв‚ѓ + 3Hв‚‚)", options:{A:"112.5 cmВі",B:"225 cmВі",C:"75 cmВі",D:"450 cmВі"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Moles Al = 4.05 Г· 27 = 0.15 mol. Ratio Al:HCl = 2:6 = 1:3, so moles HCl = 0.45 mol. Volume = 0.45 Г· 2 = 0.225 dmВі = 225 cmВі." },
  { id:"ch3_16", question:"What is the key difference between addition and condensation polymerisation?", options:{A:"Addition requires a catalyst; condensation does not",B:"Addition uses C=C monomers and produces only the polymer; condensation uses bifunctional monomers and releases a small molecule (e.g. water)",C:"Both produce water as a by-product",D:"Condensation only occurs with natural materials"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Addition: alkene monomers (C=C) в†’ polymer only. No by-product. Condensation: two functional groups react (в€’NHв‚‚ + в€’COOH в†’ nylon; в€’OH + в€’COOH в†’ polyester) releasing water (or HCl) per linkage formed." },
  { id:"ch3_17", question:"Ethanol + ethanoic acid в†’ ethyl ethanoate + water. This reaction is called", options:{A:"Hydrolysis",B:"Oxidation",C:"Esterification",D:"Saponification"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Esterification: alcohol + carboxylic acid в‡Њ ester + water, catalysed by concentrated Hв‚‚SOв‚„. The reverse (ester + water в†’ alcohol + acid) is hydrolysis. Saponification = alkaline hydrolysis of esters (soap making)." },
  { id:"ch3_18", question:"Which reagent distinguishes between an alkane and an alkene?", options:{A:"Acidified KMnOв‚„",B:"Dilute HCl",C:"NaOH solution",D:"Bromine water"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Bromine water (orange) is decolourised by alkenes (C=C + Brв‚‚ в†’ dibromoalkane) but NOT by alkanes under normal conditions. Simplest and most specific test for unsaturation in JAMB." },
  { id:"ch3_19", question:"To oxidise propan-1-ol to propanal ONLY (not propanoic acid), the correct method is", options:{A:"Excess acidified Kв‚‚Crв‚‚Oв‚‡ under reflux",B:"Acidified Kв‚‚Crв‚‚Oв‚‡, distil the aldehyde off immediately as it forms",C:"NaOH solution",D:"Concentrated Hв‚‚SOв‚„ alone"}, answer:"B", explanation:"To stop at the aldehyde: use acidified dichromate (Kв‚‚Crв‚‚Oв‚‡/Hв‚‚SOв‚„) and distil the aldehyde immediately as it forms, preventing further oxidation to carboxylic acid. Reflux with EXCESS oxidant takes it all the way to the acid." },
  { id:"ch3_20", question:"A compound has molecular formula Cв‚„Hв‚€Oв‚‚, a fruity smell, and is insoluble in water. It is most likely", options:{A:"Butanoic acid",B:"Propan-1-ol",C:"An ester",D:"Butan-1-ol"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Esters have formula Cв‚™Hв‚‚в‚™Oв‚‚ and characteristic fruity or sweet smells. Carboxylic acids with the same formula smell acrid (vinegar). Insolubility in water further supports ester identification. JAMB commonly tests ester identification by smell and formula." },
  { id:"ch3_21", question:"The element with electronic configuration 2, 8, 2 reacts with chlorine. What is the formula and bonding of the product?", options:{A:"XCl, ionic",B:"XClв‚‚, ionic",C:"XClв‚‚, covalent",D:"Xв‚‚Cl, ionic"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Configuration 2,8,2 в†’ 2 valence electrons в†’ Group II metal. Loses both to form XВІвЃє. Each Cl gains 1eвЃ» в†’ ClвЃ». Formula: XВІвЃє(ClвЃ»)в‚‚ = XClв‚‚. Metal + non-metal в†’ ionic bonding. Example: MgClв‚‚." },
  { id:"ch3_22", question:"Which observation confirms a collected gas is ammonia?", options:{A:"It extinguishes a glowing splint",B:"It turns moist red litmus paper blue and has a pungent smell",C:"It relights a glowing splint",D:"It turns limewater milky"}, answer:"B", explanation:"NHв‚ѓ is alkaline in water в†’ turns moist red litmus blue. It has a distinctive pungent smell. Relighting splint = Oв‚‚. Extinguishing splint = COв‚‚. Limewater milky = COв‚‚." },
  { id:"ch3_23", question:"The reaction Cu + 4HNOв‚ѓ(conc) в†’ Cu(NOв‚ѓ)в‚‚ + 2NOв‚‚ + 2Hв‚‚O is an example of", options:{A:"A simple acid-base reaction only",B:"A redox reaction, Cu is oxidised; N is reduced",C:"A precipitation reaction",D:"A neutralisation reaction producing only salt and water"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Cu: 0 в†’ +2 (oxidised). N: +5 (in HNOв‚ѓ) в†’ +4 (in NOв‚‚) (reduced). Concentrated HNOв‚ѓ acts as an oxidising agent, not merely a proton donor. This is why copper dissolves in HNOв‚ѓ but not HCl." },
  { id:"ch3_24", question:"How many moles of electrons are needed to reduce 1 mol of AlВівЃє to Al metal?", options:{A:"1 mole",B:"2 moles",C:"3 moles",D:"6 moles"}, answer:"C", explanation:"AlВівЃє + 3eвЃ» в†’ Al. 1 mol AlВівЃє requires 3 mol electrons = 3 Faradays = 3 Г— 96,500 C = 289,500 C. Basis for calculating electrical energy needed in aluminium electrolytic extraction." },
  { id:"ch3_25", question:"The Ksp of AgCl is 1.8 Г— 10вЃ»В№вЃ° molВІ/dmвЃ¶. What is its molar solubility in pure water?", options:{A:"1.8 Г— 10вЃ»В№вЃ° mol/dmВі",B:"1.34 Г— 10вЃ»вЃµ mol/dmВі",C:"3.6 Г— 10вЃ»В№вЃ° mol/dmВі",D:"9 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶ mol/dmВі"}, answer:"B", explanation:"AgCl в‡Њ AgвЃє + ClвЃ». Ksp = sВІ. s = в€љ(1.8 Г— 10вЃ»В№вЃ°) = 1.34 Г— 10вЃ»вЃµ mol/dmВі. Even 'insoluble' salts have a finite, non-zero solubility." },
  { id:"ch3_26", question:"Which correctly describes hydrogen bonding?", options:{A:"It occurs between all molecules containing hydrogen",B:"It forms between molecules with NвЂ“H, OвЂ“H, or FвЂ“H bonds and lone pairs on N, O, or F of neighbouring molecules",C:"Hydrogen bonds are stronger than covalent bonds",D:"Hydrogen bonding only occurs in water"}, answer:"B", explanation:"H-bonds require: H bonded to highly electronegative N, O, or F; and a lone pair on N, O, or F of a neighbouring molecule. Weaker than covalent bonds but stronger than van der Waals forces. Found in water, ethanol, DNA, proteins." },
  { id:"ch3_27", question:"A reaction doubles in rate for every 10В°C rise. If the rate at 20В°C is 0.04 mol/dmВі/s, what is the rate at 50В°C?", options:{A:"0.08 mol/dmВі/s",B:"0.16 mol/dmВі/s",C:"0.32 mol/dmВі/s",D:"0.64 mol/dmВі/s"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Rise = 30В°C = 3 increments of 10В°C. Rate = 0.04 Г— 2Ві = 0.04 Г— 8 = 0.32 mol/dmВі/s. Qв‚Ѓв‚Ђ = 2 approximation is used in both JAMB Chemistry and Biology." },
  { id:"ch3_28", question:"Which of the following is a BUFFER solution?", options:{A:"A solution of NaCl only",B:"A mixture of CHв‚ѓCOOH and CHв‚ѓCOONa",C:"A solution of NaOH only",D:"Pure water"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Buffer = weak acid + its conjugate base (salt). CHв‚ѓCOOH/CHв‚ѓCOOвЃ»: if HвЃє added в†’ CHв‚ѓCOOвЃ» absorbs it; if OHвЃ» added в†’ CHв‚ѓCOOH neutralises it. pH barely changes. Blood is buffered by Hв‚‚COв‚ѓ/HCOв‚ѓвЃ» at pH 7.4." },
  { id:"ch3_29", question:"What is the oxidation state of chromium in Kв‚‚Crв‚‚Oв‚‡? (K=+1, O=в€’2)", options:{A:"+3",B:"+4",C:"+6",D:"+7"}, answer:"C", explanation:"2(+1) + 2Cr + 7(в€’2) = 0 в†’ 2 + 2Cr в€’ 14 = 0 в†’ 2Cr = 12 в†’ Cr = +6. Potassium dichromate: powerful oxidising agent. Cr(VI) в†’ CrВівЃє (green) during oxidation reactions." },
  { id:"ch3_30", question:"The thermal decomposition of copper(II) nitrate produces", options:{A:"CuO + NOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚",B:"CuO + NO + Oв‚‚",C:"Cu + NOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚",D:"Cu(OH)в‚‚ + NOв‚ѓ"}, answer:"A", explanation:"2Cu(NOв‚ѓ)в‚‚ в†’ 2CuO + 4NOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚. Black copper oxide, brown nitrogen dioxide gas, and oxygen are produced. Transition metal nitrates generally decompose to metal oxide + NOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚. Group I nitrates decompose to nitrite + Oв‚‚." },
  { id:"ch3_31", question:"The half-equation at the cathode during electrolysis of CuSOв‚„ with copper electrodes is", options:{A:"Cu в†’ CuВІвЃє + 2eвЃ»",B:"SOв‚„ВІвЃ» в†’ SOв‚ѓ + OВІвЃ»",C:"CuВІвЃє + 2eвЃ» в†’ Cu",D:"2Hв‚‚O в†’ 4HвЃє + Oв‚‚ + 4eвЃ»"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Cathode (reduction): CuВІвЃє + 2eвЃ» в†’ Cu. Copper deposits. Anode (copper, oxidation): Cu в†’ CuВІвЃє + 2eвЃ». Copper dissolves. Net: copper transfers from anode to cathode, the basis of electroplating and copper refining. CuSOв‚„ concentration stays constant." },
  { id:"ch3_32", question:"Ethene reacts with steam over a phosphoric acid catalyst to produce", options:{A:"Ethane",B:"Diethyl ether",C:"Ethanol",D:"Ethanoic acid"}, answer:"C", explanation:"CHв‚‚=CHв‚‚ + Hв‚‚O в†’ CHв‚ѓCHв‚‚OH. Industrial ethanol synthesis by direct hydration: Hв‚ѓPOв‚„ catalyst, ~300В°C, ~60 atm. Compare with fermentation (yeast + sugars), a slower biological route." },
  { id:"ch3_33", question:"Atomic radius generally DECREASES across a period because", options:{A:"More protons are added but electrons enter the same shell, increased nuclear charge pulls electrons closer",B:"More electron shells are added with each element",C:"Neutrons repel electrons outward",D:"Atomic mass decreases across a period"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Across a period: proton number increases; electrons are added to the SAME shell. Greater nuclear charge attracts electrons more strongly in the same shell в†’ radius decreases. Down a group: new shells added в†’ radius increases." },
  { id:"ch3_34", question:"A Zn|ZnВІвЃє / Cu|CuВІвЃє electrochemical cell. Standard potentials: ZnВІвЃє/Zn = в€’0.76 V; CuВІвЃє/Cu = +0.34 V. What is the standard cell EMF?", options:{A:"в€’0.42 V",B:"0.42 V",C:"1.10 V",D:"в€’1.10 V"}, answer:"C", explanation:"EMF = EВ°(cathode) в€’ EВ°(anode) = +0.34 в€’ (в€’0.76) = 1.10 V. Zinc (more negative) = anode (oxidised); copper = cathode (reduced). Positive EMF = spontaneous reaction." },
  { id:"ch3_35", question:"What is the IUPAC name for CHв‚ѓCH(CHв‚ѓ)CHв‚‚CHв‚ѓ?", options:{A:"2-methylbutane",B:"3-methylbutane",C:"2-methylpentane",D:"Isopentane"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Longest chain including the branch = 4 carbons (butane). CHв‚ѓ branch is on carbon 2 (number from the end giving the lowest locant). IUPAC name: 2-methylbutane." },
  { id:"ch3_36", question:"0.1 mol/dmВі ethanoic acid is 1.3% dissociated. What is the approximate [HвЃє]?", options:{A:"0.1 mol/dmВі",B:"0.013 mol/dmВі",C:"0.0013 mol/dmВі",D:"1.3 mol/dmВі"}, answer:"C", explanation:"[HвЃє] = degree of dissociation Г— concentration = 0.013 Г— 0.1 = 0.0013 mol/dmВі. Compare: 0.1 mol/dmВі HCl (strong acid) gives [HвЃє] = 0.1 mol/dmВі, 77Г— higher than the weak acid at the same concentration." },
  { id:"ch3_37", question:"London dispersion forces exist in ALL molecules because", options:{A:"All molecules are polar",B:"All molecules have electrons that can create temporary dipoles",C:"All molecules contain hydrogen atoms",D:"All molecules can form hydrogen bonds"}, answer:"B", explanation:"London (dispersion/van der Waals) forces arise from instantaneous temporary dipoles due to electron movement. They exist in ALL molecules, polar and non-polar. They increase with molecular mass (more electrons = larger temporary dipoles = stronger forces, higher boiling points)." },
  { id:"ch3_38", question:"Ionisation energies of element X (kJ/mol): 1st: 496; 2nd: 4562; 3rd: 6910. In which group is X?", options:{A:"Group I",B:"Group II",C:"Group III",D:"Group VII"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Huge jump between 1st (496) and 2nd (4562) IE, the 2nd electron is in an inner shell. Only 1 electron is easily removed в†’ 1 valence electron в†’ Group I. (This is sodium: IEв‚Ѓ = 496 kJ/mol.)" },
  { id:"ch3_39", question:"When zinc reacts with dilute Hв‚‚SOв‚„, what type of reaction occurs and what gas is produced?", options:{A:"Displacement reaction; Hв‚‚ gas",B:"Neutralisation reaction; COв‚‚ gas",C:"Combustion reaction; SOв‚‚ gas",D:"Hydration reaction; Hв‚‚O only"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Zn + Hв‚‚SOв‚„ в†’ ZnSOв‚„ + Hв‚‚. Zinc displaces hydrogen from the acid, a displacement (redox) reaction. Zn is oxidised (0 в†’ +2); H is reduced (+1 в†’ 0). Colourless Hв‚‚ gas is produced, confirmed by squeaky pop with a lit splint." },
  { id:"ch3_40", question:"In the Contact Process for making sulphuric acid, SOв‚‚ is oxidised to SOв‚ѓ. Which conditions are used and why is the temperature a compromise?", options:{A:"High temperature (600В°C) and high pressure for maximum rate and yield",B:"Moderate temperature (450В°C) and atmospheric pressure, higher temperature increases rate but decreases equilibrium yield; a compromise is reached",C:"Low temperature (100В°C) to maximise yield without a catalyst",D:"Very high pressure to force all SOв‚‚ to convert to SOв‚ѓ"}, answer:"B", explanation:"2SOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚ в‡Њ 2SOв‚ѓ О”H = в€’ve (exothermic). High temperature в†’ faster rate but shifts equilibrium LEFT (Le Chatelier) в†’ less SOв‚ѓ. Low temperature в†’ good yield but very slow. Compromise: 450В°C with Vв‚‚Oв‚… catalyst. Pressure is near atmospheric (little benefit from high pressure for this reaction)." }
]; // end Chemistry


// в”Ђв”Ђ PHYSICS в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
DB["Physics"][3] = [
  { id:"ph3_1", question:"A stone is thrown vertically upward at 20 m/s. What is the maximum height reached? (g = 10 m/sВІ)", options:{A:"40 m",B:"20 m",C:"10 m",D:"80 m"}, answer:"B", explanation:"At max height v = 0. Using vВІ = uВІ в€’ 2gh: 0 = 400 в€’ 20h в†’ h = 20 m. Alternatively: time to top = u/g = 2 s; h = ut в€’ ВЅgtВІ = 40 в€’ 20 = 20 m." },
  { id:"ph3_2", question:"A body starts from rest, accelerates at 3 m/sВІ for 6 s, then moves at constant velocity for 4 s. Total distance covered?", options:{A:"54 m",B:"72 m",C:"126 m",D:"162 m"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Phase 1: sв‚Ѓ = ВЅatВІ = ВЅ Г— 3 Г— 36 = 54 m; v = 3 Г— 6 = 18 m/s. Phase 2: sв‚‚ = 18 Г— 4 = 72 m. Total = 54 + 72 = 126 m." },
  { id:"ph3_3", question:"A 10 kg block rests on a 30В° incline. What is the component of weight ALONG the slope? (g = 10 m/sВІ, sin 30В° = 0.5)", options:{A:"50 N",B:"86.6 N",C:"100 N",D:"25 N"}, answer:"A", explanation:"W = mg = 100 N. Component along slope = W sin Оё = 100 Г— 0.5 = 50 N (tending to slide the block down). Normal component = W cos 30В° = 86.6 N." },
  { id:"ph3_4", question:"A bullet of mass 20 g is fired from a 4 kg gun at 400 m/s. What is the gun's recoil velocity?", options:{A:"80 m/s",B:"2 m/s",C:"0.5 m/s",D:"8 m/s"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Conservation of momentum: 0 = (0.02)(400) + (4)v. 4v = в€’8 в†’ v = 2 m/s recoil. Initial total momentum = 0 (both at rest)." },
  { id:"ph3_5", question:"A 0.5 kg object is swung in a horizontal circle of radius 0.8 m at 4 m/s. What centripetal force is required?", options:{A:"1.6 N",B:"10 N",C:"2 N",D:"6.4 N"}, answer:"B", explanation:"F = mvВІ/r = (0.5 Г— 16) Г· 0.8 = 8 Г· 0.8 = 10 N. Centripetal force is directed toward the centre, provided by tension in the string." },
  { id:"ph3_6", question:"A 60 kg person stands on a scale in a lift that reads 720 N. What is the lift's acceleration? (g = 10 m/sВІ)", options:{A:"2 m/sВІ downward",B:"2 m/sВІ upward",C:"12 m/sВІ upward",D:"Zero, reading is normal"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Normal weight = 600 N. Scale reads 720 N > 600 N в†’ net upward force = 120 N. a = F/m = 120/60 = 2 m/sВІ upward. If scale < weight в†’ downward acceleration." },
  { id:"ph3_7", question:"A 400 W motor pumps water to a height of 10 m. How many kg can it lift per second? (g = 10 m/sВІ)", options:{A:"4 kg/s",B:"0.4 kg/s",C:"40 kg/s",D:"400 kg/s"}, answer:"A", explanation:"P = mgh/t в†’ mass/time = P/(gh) = 400/(10 Г— 10) = 4 kg/s." },
  { id:"ph3_8", question:"A 25 О© heater is connected to a 250 V supply. How much heat energy is produced in 2 minutes?", options:{A:"300,000 J",B:"30,000 J",C:"150,000 J",D:"1,500 J"}, answer:"A", explanation:"I = V/R = 10 A. P = IВІR = 100 Г— 25 = 2500 W. E = Pt = 2500 Г— 120 s = 300,000 J." },
  { id:"ph3_9", question:"A step-up transformer: 400 primary turns, 3200 secondary turns, primary current = 8 A, 100% efficiency. What is the secondary current?", options:{A:"64 A",B:"1 A",C:"8 A",D:"0.5 A"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Vв‚›/Vв‚љ = Nв‚›/Nв‚љ = 8. At 100% efficiency: Iв‚љ Vв‚љ = Iв‚› Vв‚› в†’ Iв‚› = Iв‚љ/8 = 8/8 = 1 A. Step-up transformers increase voltage but decrease current by the same factor." },
  { id:"ph3_10", question:"A wire of length 2 m and cross-section 0.5 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶ mВІ has resistance 3.2 О©. What is the resistivity?", options:{A:"8 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ· О©В·m",B:"0.8 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶ О©В·m",C:"3.2 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶ О©В·m",D:"1.6 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ· О©В·m"}, answer:"A", explanation:"ПЃ = RA/L = (3.2 Г— 0.5 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶) Г· 2 = 1.6 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶ Г· 2 = 8 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ· О©В·m." },
  { id:"ph3_11", question:"A sound source emitting 400 Hz moves toward a stationary observer at 20 m/s. Speed of sound = 340 m/s. Observed frequency?", options:{A:"377 Hz",B:"400 Hz",C:"425 Hz",D:"447 Hz"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Doppler (source toward observer): fвЂІ = f Г— v/(v в€’ vв‚›) = 400 Г— 340/320 = 425 Hz. Source moving toward = higher observed frequency. Source moving away: fвЂІ = f Г— v/(v + vв‚›)." },
  { id:"ph3_12", question:"Two parallel plates are 4 mm apart and connected to 120 V. What is the electric field strength between them?", options:{A:"480 V/m",B:"30,000 V/m",C:"0.033 V/m",D:"480,000 V/m"}, answer:"B", explanation:"E = V/d = 120 Г· (4 Г— 10вЃ»Ві) = 30,000 V/m. For uniform field between parallel plates: E is constant and directed from positive to negative plate." },
  { id:"ph3_13", question:"An О±-particle (вЃґв‚‚He) is emitted from ВІВівЃёв‚‰в‚‚U. What is the resulting nucleus?", options:{A:"ВІВівЃґв‚‰в‚ЂTh",B:"ВІВівЃґв‚‰в‚ЃPa",C:"ВІВівЃёв‚‰в‚ЂTh",D:"ВІВівЃ¶в‚‰в‚‚U"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Alpha decay: mass number в€’4, atomic number в€’2. ВІВівЃёв‚‰в‚‚U в†’ ВІВівЃґв‚‰в‚ЂX. Element 90 = Thorium. Product = ВІВівЃґв‚‰в‚ЂTh. First step in the uranium-238 decay series." },
  { id:"ph3_14", question:"The activity of a source falls from 4000 dis/s to 500 dis/s in 6 hours. What is the half-life?", options:{A:"1 hour",B:"2 hours",C:"3 hours",D:"6 hours"}, answer:"B", explanation:"4000 в†’ 2000 в†’ 1000 в†’ 500: three halvings. 3 half-lives = 6 hours в†’ half-life = 2 hours. Activity and atom number both follow the same exponential decay." },
  { id:"ph3_15", question:"In the fission reaction: ВІВівЃµв‚‰в‚‚U + В№в‚Ђn в†’ В№вЃґВ№в‚…в‚†Ba + вЃ№ВІв‚ѓв‚†Kr + x В№в‚Ђn. What is x?", options:{A:"1",B:"2",C:"3",D:"4"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Mass conservation: 235 + 1 = 141 + 92 + x в†’ 236 = 233 + x в†’ x = 3. Three neutrons released per fission, these can trigger further fissions, creating a chain reaction." },
  { id:"ph3_16", question:"A current-carrying conductor of length 0.5 m carrying 3 A is perpendicular to a 0.4 T magnetic field. What force acts on it?", options:{A:"0.6 N",B:"6 N",C:"0.06 N",D:"60 N"}, answer:"A", explanation:"F = BIL sin Оё = 0.4 Г— 3 Г— 0.5 Г— sin 90В° = 0.6 N. Direction by Fleming's Left-Hand Rule. This is the motor effect." },
  { id:"ph3_17", question:"A 100 ВµF capacitor is charged to 50 V. What charge is stored?", options:{A:"5000 ВµC",B:"2 ВµC",C:"0.002 C",D:"5 mC"}, answer:"D", explanation:"Q = CV = 100 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶ Г— 50 = 5 Г— 10вЃ»Ві C = 5 mC. Energy stored = ВЅCVВІ = ВЅ Г— 100 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ¶ Г— 2500 = 0.125 J." },
  { id:"ph3_18", question:"A body executes SHM with amplitude 0.1 m and angular frequency 5 rad/s. What is its maximum velocity?", options:{A:"0.5 m/s",B:"2 m/s",C:"0.02 m/s",D:"5 m/s"}, answer:"A", explanation:"v_max = AП‰ = 0.1 Г— 5 = 0.5 m/s. Maximum velocity occurs at the equilibrium position (x = 0). Maximum acceleration = AП‰ВІ = 0.1 Г— 25 = 2.5 m/sВІ (occurs at maximum displacement)." },
  { id:"ph3_19", question:"Light of wavelength 600 nm enters a medium of refractive index 1.5. What is its wavelength in the medium?", options:{A:"400 nm",B:"900 nm",C:"600 nm",D:"300 nm"}, answer:"A", explanation:"О»_medium = О»_air / n = 600 / 1.5 = 400 nm. Frequency is unchanged; speed and wavelength decrease proportionally when entering a denser medium." },
  { id:"ph3_20", question:"A thermometer reads 77В°F. What is this in Kelvin?", options:{A:"298 K",B:"350 K",C:"25 K",D:"303 K"}, answer:"A", explanation:"В°C = (77 в€’ 32) Г— 5/9 = 45 Г— 5/9 = 25В°C. K = 25 + 273 = 298 K." },
  { id:"ph3_21", question:"A convex mirror has focal length 15 cm. Object placed 30 cm in front. Image distance?", options:{A:"10 cm behind mirror (virtual)",B:"10 cm in front (real)",C:"30 cm behind mirror",D:"At infinity"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Using new Cartesian sign convention (distances in front of mirror are negative): u = в€’30 cm, f = +15 cm (convex mirror: focal point is behind mirror, so positive). 1/v = 1/f в€’ 1/u = 1/15 в€’ 1/(в€’30) = 1/15 + 1/30 = 2/30 + 1/30 = 3/30. v = +10 cm. Positive v means the image is 10 cm behind the mirror: virtual, upright, and diminished. Convex mirrors always produce virtual images." },
  { id:"ph3_22", question:"An ideal gas at 27В°C occupies 2 L at 1 atm. Compressed to 0.5 L and heated to 127В°C. New pressure?", options:{A:"4 atm",B:"5.33 atm",C:"3 atm",D:"8 atm"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Pв‚ЃVв‚Ѓ/Tв‚Ѓ = Pв‚‚Vв‚‚/Tв‚‚. Tв‚Ѓ = 300 K, Tв‚‚ = 400 K. Pв‚‚ = (1 Г— 2 Г— 400)/(300 Г— 0.5) = 800/150 = 5.33 atm." },
  { id:"ph3_23", question:"A 2 kg block slides down a frictionless slope of height 3 m. Speed at the bottom? (g = 10 m/sВІ)", options:{A:"7.75 m/s",B:"в€љ60 m/s",C:"30 m/s",D:"60 m/s"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Conservation of energy: mgh = ВЅmvВІ. vВІ = 2gh = 60. v = в€љ60 в‰€ 7.75 m/s. Mass cancels, speed is independent of mass on a frictionless incline." },
  { id:"ph3_24", question:"Work done in stretching a spring by 10 cm if k = 200 N/m?", options:{A:"20 J",B:"10 J",C:"1 J",D:"2000 J"}, answer:"C", explanation:"W = ВЅkeВІ = ВЅ Г— 200 Г— (0.1)ВІ = ВЅ Г— 200 Г— 0.01 = 1 J. This elastic potential energy is stored in the spring and can be fully recovered on release (ideal spring)." },
  { id:"ph3_25", question:"A Wheatstone bridge: Rв‚Ѓ = 100 О©, Rв‚‚ = 150 О©, Rв‚ѓ = 200 О©, Rx = unknown. At balance, what is Rx?", options:{A:"133 О©",B:"300 О©",C:"50 О©",D:"250 О©"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Balance condition: Rв‚Ѓ/Rв‚‚ = Rв‚ѓ/Rx в†’ 100/150 = 200/Rx в†’ Rx = 300 О©. At balance, no current flows through the galvanometer." },
  { id:"ph3_26", question:"A string vibrates at fundamental frequency 200 Hz. What is the frequency of the 3rd harmonic?", options:{A:"400 Hz",B:"600 Hz",C:"800 Hz",D:"200 Hz"}, answer:"B", explanation:"nth harmonic = n Г— fundamental. 3rd harmonic = 3 Г— 200 = 600 Hz. In strings fixed at both ends, all harmonics (integer multiples of fundamental) are possible." },
  { id:"ph3_27", question:"Two charges +4 ВµC and +9 ВµC are 30 cm apart. At what distance from the +4 ВµC charge is the electric field zero?", options:{A:"12 cm",B:"18 cm",C:"15 cm",D:"The field is never zero between like charges"}, answer:"A", explanation:"For E = 0: kГ—4/rВІ = kГ—9/(0.30в€’r)ВІ. Take square roots: 2/r = 3/(0.30в€’r) в†’ 2(0.30в€’r) = 3r в†’ 0.60 = 5r в†’ r = 0.12 m = 12 cm. Zero point is closer to the weaker charge." },
  { id:"ph3_28", question:"What is the critical angle for a glass-water interface? (n_glass = 1.5, n_water = 1.33)", options:{A:"62.5В°",B:"41.8В°",C:"48.6В°",D:"27.5В°"}, answer:"A", explanation:"At critical angle: n_glass Г— sin C = n_water Г— sin 90В°. sin C = 1.33/1.5 = 0.887. C = sinвЃ»В№(0.887) в‰€ 62.5В°. Glass-water interface has a larger critical angle than glass-air (в‰€41.8В°) because n_water > n_air." },
  { id:"ph3_29", question:"An object is placed 30 cm in front of a concave mirror with focal length 10 cm. Where is the image formed?", options:{A:"15 cm in front of mirror (real)",B:"15 cm behind mirror (virtual)",C:"30 cm in front (real)",D:"At infinity"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Mirror formula: 1/v + 1/u = 1/f. Using sign convention (real positive): u = в€’30, f = в€’10. 1/v = 1/(в€’10) в€’ 1/(в€’30) = в€’3/30 + 1/30 = в€’2/30 в†’ v = в€’15 cm. Negative = real, in front of concave mirror." },
  { id:"ph3_30", question:"The internal resistance of a cell is 0.5 О© and its EMF is 6 V. If connected to a 5.5 О© external resistor, what is the terminal voltage?", options:{A:"5.5 V",B:"6 V",C:"0.5 V",D:"3 V"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Total resistance = 5.5 + 0.5 = 6 О©. Current I = EMF/R_total = 6/6 = 1 A. Terminal voltage = EMF в€’ Ir = 6 в€’ (1 Г— 0.5) = 5.5 V. Terminal voltage < EMF due to internal resistance voltage drop." },
  { id:"ph3_31", question:"A projectile is launched horizontally from a 45 m cliff. How long does it take to hit the ground? (g = 10 m/sВІ)", options:{A:"3 s",B:"4.5 s",C:"9 s",D:"в€љ90 s"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Vertical: h = ВЅgtВІ в†’ 45 = ВЅ Г— 10 Г— tВІ в†’ tВІ = 9 в†’ t = 3 s. Horizontal velocity does not affect the time of fall, only the vertical component of motion determines flight time." },
  { id:"ph3_32", question:"The efficiency of a machine is 75% and the load is 600 N lifted 4 m. What effort is needed to move the effort through 8 m?", options:{A:"200 N",B:"400 N",C:"450 N",D:"100 N"}, answer:"B", explanation:"Work output = 600 Г— 4 = 2400 J. Efficiency = Work output / Work input. 0.75 = 2400/W_input в†’ W_input = 3200 J. Effort = W_input/effort distance = 3200/8 = 400 N." },
  { id:"ph3_33", question:"A photon has wavelength 500 nm. What is its energy? (h = 6.63 Г— 10вЃ»ВівЃґ JВ·s, c = 3 Г— 10вЃё m/s)", options:{A:"3.98 Г— 10вЃ»В№вЃ№ J",B:"3.98 Г— 10вЃ»ВІвЃё J",C:"1.99 Г— 10вЃ»В№вЃё J",D:"6.63 Г— 10вЃ»ВІвЃё J"}, answer:"A", explanation:"E = hf = hc/О» = (6.63 Г— 10вЃ»ВівЃґ Г— 3 Г— 10вЃё) / (500 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ№) = 1.989 Г— 10вЃ»ВІвЃµ / 5 Г— 10вЃ»вЃ· = 3.98 Г— 10вЃ»В№вЃ№ J. Shorter wavelength в†’ higher frequency в†’ greater energy." },
  { id:"ph3_34", question:"3 kg of water is heated from 20В°C to 70В°C. How much energy is required? (SHC of water = 4200 J/kgВ·В°C)", options:{A:"630,000 J",B:"63,000 J",C:"6,300 J",D:"126,000 J"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Q = mcО”T = 3 Г— 4200 Г— 50 = 630,000 J = 630 kJ. О”T = 70 в€’ 20 = 50В°C. This is a classic JAMB thermal energy calculation." },
  { id:"ph3_35", question:"A 500 g metal sample absorbs 20,000 J of heat, rising from 25В°C to 125В°C. What is its specific heat capacity?", options:{A:"400 J/kgВ·В°C",B:"200 J/kgВ·В°C",C:"800 J/kgВ·В°C",D:"1000 J/kgВ·В°C"}, answer:"A", explanation:"c = Q/(mО”T) = 20,000 / (0.5 Г— 100) = 20,000/50 = 400 J/kgВ·В°C. О”T = 125 в€’ 25 = 100В°C. Mass must be in kg: 500 g = 0.5 kg." },
  { id:"ph3_36", question:"A charge of 3 A flows for 4 minutes through a resistor. How much charge passes?", options:{A:"720 C",B:"12 C",C:"48 C",D:"0.75 C"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Q = It = 3 Г— (4 Г— 60) = 3 Г— 240 = 720 C. Always convert time to seconds. Charge (coulombs) = current (amperes) Г— time (seconds)." },
  { id:"ph3_37", question:"For total internal reflection to occur, light must travel from", options:{A:"A less dense medium to a more dense medium at any angle",B:"A more optically dense medium to a less dense medium at an angle greater than or equal to the critical angle",C:"Air to glass at 90В°",D:"Any medium to any other medium at 45В°"}, answer:"B", explanation:"TIR requires: (1) light in the denser medium; (2) angle of incidence в‰Ґ critical angle. If angle < critical angle, refraction occurs. At the critical angle exactly, the refracted ray travels along the interface (90В° to normal)." },
  { id:"ph3_38", question:"A transformer has 200 primary turns and 1000 secondary turns. If 240 V AC is applied to the primary, what is the secondary voltage?", options:{A:"48 V",B:"240 V",C:"1200 V",D:"2400 V"}, answer:"C", explanation:"Vв‚›/Vв‚љ = Nв‚›/Nв‚љ в†’ Vв‚› = 240 Г— (1000/200) = 240 Г— 5 = 1200 V. This is a step-up transformer, secondary voltage > primary voltage." },
  { id:"ph3_39", question:"An object of mass 4 kg moving at 10 m/s collides with a stationary 6 kg object. They stick together. What is their common velocity?", options:{A:"4 m/s",B:"6 m/s",C:"10 m/s",D:"2 m/s"}, answer:"A", explanation:"Conservation of momentum: mв‚Ѓuв‚Ѓ = (mв‚Ѓ + mв‚‚)v. 4 Г— 10 = (4 + 6)v в†’ 40 = 10v в†’ v = 4 m/s. This is a perfectly inelastic collision, kinetic energy is NOT conserved (some is lost to heat and deformation)." },
  { id:"ph3_40", question:"A parallel circuit has resistors of 4 О©, 6 О©, and 12 О© connected across a 12 V battery. What is the total current from the battery?", options:{A:"3 A",B:"6 A",C:"1 A",D:"9 A"}, answer:"B", explanation:"In parallel, same voltage across each: Iв‚Ѓ = 12/4 = 3 A; Iв‚‚ = 12/6 = 2 A; Iв‚ѓ = 12/12 = 1 A. Total I = 3 + 2 + 1 = 6 A. Alternatively: 1/R_total = 1/4 + 1/6 + 1/12 = 3/12 + 2/12 + 1/12 = 6/12 в†’ R = 2 О©. I = 12/2 = 6 A." }
]; // end Physics


